Kubernetes Architecture
=========================

Kubernetes has two main parts:
1) Control Plane (Master) â†’ Brain of the cluster
2) Worker Nodes â†’ Where your applications actually run

1) Control Plane Components (Master / Brain)

âœ… Step 1: API Server (kube-apiserver)
This is the main entry point.
When you run kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml, it goes to API Server
All requests (UI, CLI, CI/CD) talk to API Server only
ğŸ‘‰ In short: API Server = Front door of Kubernetes
âœ… Step 2: etcd (Database)
This is the key-value database of Kubernetes.
Stores cluster state like:
Pods, services, deployments
secrets, configmaps
node info
ğŸ‘‰ In short: etcd = Kubernetes brain memory
âœ… Step 3: Scheduler (kube-scheduler)
Now Kubernetes decides: â€œWhich node should run this pod?â€
Scheduler checks:
CPU / memory availability
node labels, taints, affinity rules
Then it assigns pod to the best node.
ğŸ‘‰ In short: Scheduler = Pod placement manager
âœ… Step 4: Controller Manager (kube-controller-manager)
This component ensures the cluster is always in the desired state.
Example:
You said replicas = 3
If one pod dies, controller creates another pod
It handles controllers like:
Node controller
Replication controller
Job controller
ğŸ‘‰ In short: Controller Manager = Auto-correction system
âœ… Step 5: Cloud Controller Manager (in cloud like AWS/Azure)
This is used in cloud environments to manage:
Load balancers
volumes
cloud networking
ğŸ‘‰ In short: Cloud Controller = Kubernetes talking to cloud services
2) Worker Node Components (Where app runs)
âœ… Step 6: Node (Worker Machine)
Worker node can be:
VM
physical server
cloud instance
This is where your pods run.
âœ… Step 7: Kubelet
Kubelet is like the agent inside every node.
It talks to API server
It ensures containers are running properly
If pod needs to start â†’ kubelet starts it using container runtime
ğŸ‘‰ In short: Kubelet = Node manager agent
âœ… Step 8: Container Runtime (Docker / containerd / CRI-O)
This is the tool that actually runs containers.
Kubernetes doesnâ€™t run containers directly â€” runtime does.
ğŸ‘‰ In short: Runtime = Engine that runs containers
âœ… Step 9: Kube-proxy (Networking)
Kube-proxy handles:
service networking
load balancing inside cluster
routes traffic to correct pod
Example: Service â†’ forwards traffic to pod1, pod2, pod3.
ğŸ‘‰ In short: kube-proxy = Traffic router inside cluster


